Octane Prediction Using Multivariate Regression
Forensic Chemistry VT2026
Assignment Overview

This project investigates the use of multivariate regression techniques to predict octane values from infrared (IR) spectroscopy data. The dataset contains petroleum samples with measured octane values and corresponding IR spectral variables.

Three regression methods were implemented and compared:

Multiple Linear Regression (MLR)
Principal Component Regression (PCR)
Partial Least Squares Regression (PLS)

The objective is to determine which model provides the best predictive performance for octane concentration based on IR spectral measurements.

Dataset

The dataset (octane.csv) contains:

Column 1: Octane value (response variable)
Columns 2 onward: Infrared (IR) spectral measurements (predictor variables)
Methodology
1. Data Preparation
Data imported into R.
Response variable (octane) separated from predictor variables (IR spectra).
Dataset split into:
70% Training Set
30% Test Set
Predictor variables centered and scaled using the caret package.
2. Multiple Linear Regression (MLR)

A linear regression model was fitted using all available IR variables as predictors.

3. Principal Component Regression (PCR)

PCR was performed using cross-validation to reduce dimensionality and handle multicollinearity among spectral variables.

Three principal components were selected, explaining approximately 96.41% of the variance.

4. Partial Least Squares Regression (PLS)

PLS regression was performed using cross-validation. Three latent variables were used for prediction.

5. Model Evaluation

Model performance was evaluated on the test dataset using:

Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)

A lower RMSE indicates better predictive capability.

Software and Packages

The analysis was conducted in R using the following packages:

install.packages("tidyverse")
install.packages("pls")
install.packages("caret")

library(tidyverse)
library(pls)
library(caret)
Results
Model	RMSE
MLR	33.4875978
PCR	0.3093043
PLS	0.2573786
Best Model

The model with the lowest RMSE was considered to have the best predictive performance for octane prediction.

Visualisation

Observed vs Predicted plots were generated for:

Multiple Linear Regression (MLR)
Principal Component Regression (PCR)
Partial Least Squares Regression (PLS)

These plots allow visual assessment of prediction accuracy and model performance.

